eased end-systolic volume","Decreased stroke volume, decreased end-diastolic volume","Decreased stroke volume, decreased end-systolic volume","Increased stroke volume, increased end-systolic volume"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIncreased inotropy of the heart results in \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased stroke volume\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased end-systolic volume\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the correct answer because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncreased inotropy means the heart contracts more forcefully.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis stronger contraction leads to more blood being ejected from the ventricles during systole, increasing the stroke volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe more forceful contraction also results in less blood remaining in the ventricles at the end of systole, decreasing the end-systolic volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Increased inotropy leads to increased stroke volume and decreased end-systolic volume.","Inotropy refers to the strength of cardiac muscle contraction."],"references":["Tortora, G. J., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Cooke, J., Di Pietro, F., Diversi, T., ... \u0026 Summers, S.. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 3rd Asia-Pacific Edition. 2022. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kaplan, J.A. Kaplan\u0027s Essentials of Cardiac Anesthesia. 2018. 2nd edition. Elsevier. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1016/C2012-0-06151-0"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43448"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14405"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43448"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T16:57:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T16:57:54+10:30"},"relati